// Beyond 21st Century Beauty Academy — CA Cosmetology State Board Exam Questions
// April 2026 BBC/PSI Content Outline — Original questions, not copied from PSI
const QUESTION_BANK = {
  sic: [
    { q: "When a cosmetologist accidentally cuts a client's skin during a service, the FIRST action should be to:", opts:["Apply a styptic pencil immediately","Stop the service, put on gloves, and follow standard precautions","Rinse the area with hydrogen peroxide","Continue the service and monitor the wound"], ans: 1, exp: "Standard/Universal Precautions require stopping the service and donning gloves before any contact with blood or body fluids. This protects both the client and the cosmetologist from cross-contamination." },
    { q: "Which EPA-registered disinfectant classification is required for tools that contact non-intact skin in a California salon?", opts:["Sanitizer","Bacteriostatic agent","Hospital-grade disinfectant","Sterilant"], ans: 2, exp: "Hospital-grade disinfectants are required for implements contacting broken or non-intact skin. They kill a broader spectrum of pathogens than sanitizers alone." },
    { q: "Safety Data Sheets (SDS) must be accessible in the salon for:", opts:["Customer reference only","All chemical products used in the salon","Only products that contain ammonia","Products costing more than $50"], ans: 1, exp: "OSHA's Hazard Communication Standard requires SDS for every chemical product in the workplace. They must be accessible to all employees at all times during work shifts." },
    { q: "The correct order of decontamination steps for reusable metal implements is:", opts:["Disinfect then Clean then Rinse","Clean then Rinse then Disinfect","Sterilize then Clean then Store","Rinse then Sanitize then Store"], ans: 1, exp: "You must remove visible debris (clean) and rinse before disinfection. Disinfectants cannot penetrate organic matter, so cleaning first is essential for effective decontamination." },
    { q: "A client arrives for a haircut showing visible signs of head lice (pediculosis). The cosmetologist should:", opts:["Perform the service using extra gloves","Refer the client to a physician and decline service","Apply a medicated shampoo and proceed","Ask the client to return after self-treating at home"], ans: 1, exp: "Pediculosis is a contraindication for salon services. The cosmetologist must professionally decline, recommend the client seek treatment, and sanitize and disinfect the workstation." },
    { q: "The minimum contact time required for most EPA-registered quaternary ammonium disinfectants on implements is:", opts:["30 seconds","5 minutes","10 minutes","24 hours"], ans: 2, exp: "Most quaternary ammonium solutions require a minimum 10-minute contact time to be effective. Always follow the manufacturer label since contact times vary by product." },
    { q: "Electrical safety in the salon requires that thermal appliances:", opts:["Be stored unplugged and cooled before storage","May share extension cords to save outlets","Should be left on between clients for efficiency","Only need inspection once a year"], ans: 0, exp: "Thermal appliances such as flat irons and curling irons should always be unplugged and fully cooled before storage to prevent fires, burns, or electrical hazards." },
    { q: "In California salons, single-use items such as neck strips and cotton rounds must be:", opts:["Disinfected and reused if not soiled","Discarded after one client use","Stored in a labeled closed container for 24 hours","Boiled to sterilize before reuse"], ans: 1, exp: "Single-use items are designed for one client only. Reusing them violates California BBC regulations and risks cross-contamination." },
    { q: "Proper ventilation is required in nail service areas primarily to:", opts:["Reduce chemical fume exposure for both clients and technicians","Maintain humidity for nail product performance","Keep product prices low","Comply with fire codes only"], ans: 0, exp: "Nail products release volatile organic compounds and potentially harmful fumes. OSHA and California regulations require adequate ventilation to protect respiratory health." },
    { q: "A cosmetologist notices a bottle of chemical relaxer is leaking. The correct action is to:", opts:["Pour the contents into an unlabeled container","Cap it tightly and continue using it","Review the SDS for handling and disposal instructions","Place it near an open window and ignore it"], ans: 2, exp: "The SDS Section 6 contains spill and leak procedures. Cosmetologists must follow SDS instructions for safe handling, containment, and disposal of chemical spills." },
    { q: "The primary purpose of draping a client before a chemical service is to:", opts:["Protect the client's clothing from chemical damage","Make the client comfortable","Improve access to the hair","Prevent the client from moving"], ans: 0, exp: "Proper draping with a chemical cape and neck strip protects the client's skin and clothing from chemical burns and staining, which is a safety requirement under California BBC regulations." },
    { q: "Which type of infection is caused by a pathogen that can only survive inside a living host cell?", opts:["Bacterial infection","Fungal infection","Viral infection","Parasitic infection"], ans: 2, exp: "Viruses are obligate intracellular parasites that require living host cells to replicate. Common examples in the salon context include influenza, hepatitis B, and HIV." },
    { q: "The three levels of decontamination in order from lowest to highest efficacy are:", opts:["Sterilization, disinfection, sanitization","Sanitization, disinfection, sterilization","Disinfection, sterilization, sanitization","Sanitization, sterilization, disinfection"], ans: 1, exp: "Sanitization reduces pathogens to safe levels; disinfection destroys most pathogens on non-porous surfaces; sterilization eliminates all microbial life including spores." },
    { q: "Bloodborne pathogens in the salon setting are most commonly transmitted through:", opts:["Airborne droplets during shampooing","Contact with contaminated blood or body fluids via broken skin","Sharing towels between clients","Improperly stored hair color products"], ans: 1, exp: "OSHA's Bloodborne Pathogen Standard identifies direct contact with infected blood or body fluids through cuts or abrasions as the primary transmission route for pathogens like HIV and hepatitis B." },
    { q: "After using an implement on a client, the first step before placing it in disinfectant solution is:", opts:["Soaking for 5 minutes","Physically scrubbing off all visible debris","Rinsing with hot water only","Spraying with alcohol"], ans: 1, exp: "Physically removing all visible debris is mandatory before disinfection. Organic matter acts as a protective barrier for pathogens and prevents disinfectants from reaching the surface." },
    { q: "Which federal agency regulates the safety of professional salon disinfectants?", opts:["FDA","EPA","OSHA","CDC"], ans: 1, exp: "The EPA registers and regulates salon disinfectants as pesticides. Products must carry an EPA registration number on the label. OSHA regulates workplace safety procedures." },
    { q: "A cosmetologist who works with chemical services should wear gloves to protect against:", opts:["Dry hands from frequent handwashing","Allergic sensitization and chemical dermatitis from repeated chemical exposure","Color staining that is only cosmetic","Bacterial infection from the client's hair"], ans: 1, exp: "Repeated skin contact with chemicals like hair color and relaxers can cause allergic sensitization, a progressive immune reaction. Gloves prevent dermatitis and sensitization." },
    { q: "Phenolic disinfectants are appropriate for salon use because they:", opts:["Are safe to use directly on skin","Are effective against a broad spectrum of bacteria, fungi, and viruses on hard surfaces","Can be safely poured down the drain without dilution","Work faster than quaternary ammonium compounds"], ans: 1, exp: "Phenolics are broad-spectrum disinfectants effective on hard non-porous surfaces against bacteria, fungi, and many viruses. They are not safe for skin contact and must be used at the specified dilution." },
    { q: "Which of the following describes a contagious condition?", opts:["A condition that is hereditary","A condition that can spread from person to person","A condition caused by environmental factors","A non-infectious chronic skin condition"], ans: 1, exp: "A contagious (communicable) condition can be transmitted from one person to another directly or indirectly. Cosmetologists must recognize contagious conditions as contraindications." },
    { q: "The term pathogen refers to:", opts:["Any chemical that damages hair","A microorganism capable of causing disease","A harmless bacteria found on the skin","An environmental allergen"], ans: 1, exp: "A pathogen is any disease-causing microorganism, including bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites. Not all microorganisms are pathogens; the skin naturally hosts beneficial non-pathogenic bacteria." },
    { q: "Sterilization in a salon setting is typically achieved using:", opts:["Quaternary ammonium solution","Bleach diluted 1:10 with water","An autoclave (steam under pressure)","Ultraviolet light cabinet"], ans: 2, exp: "An autoclave uses pressurized steam at high temperatures to destroy all microbial life including spores. UV light cabinets and quat solutions achieve disinfection only, not sterilization." },
    { q: "OSHA requires an employer in a salon to offer hepatitis B vaccination to employees who:", opts:["Request it at any time","Have occupational exposure to blood or other potentially infectious materials","Have been employed for more than one year","Work primarily with chemical services"], ans: 1, exp: "OSHA's Bloodborne Pathogen Standard requires employers to offer hepatitis B vaccination at no cost to employees with occupational exposure risk." },
    { q: "Safe water temperature for shampooing clients is generally between:", opts:["50-70 degrees F","100-110 degrees F","130-150 degrees F","Below 70 degrees F"], ans: 1, exp: "Water between 100 and 110 degrees F is comfortable for most clients without causing scalp burns. Always check water temperature on your inner wrist before applying it to the client's scalp." },
    { q: "A fumigant or disinfecting cabinet using formaldehyde tablets is:", opts:["The most effective method for disinfecting metal implements","No longer approved by California BBC for disinfection","Required for all salons by state law","Only appropriate for nail implements"], ans: 1, exp: "The California Board of Barbering and Cosmetology does not approve formaldehyde fumigant cabinets for disinfection. Wet disinfection using EPA-registered products is required." },
    { q: "After disinfection, implements should be stored in:", opts:["An open container on the workstation","A clean covered or closed container to prevent recontamination","A UV light box with the lid open","Wrapped in a paper towel in the drawer"], ans: 1, exp: "After disinfection, implements must be stored in a clean, closed or covered container to prevent recontamination before the next use." },
    { q: "If a client develops hives or difficulty breathing during a chemical service, the cosmetologist should:", opts:["Reduce the product and complete the service quickly","Remove the product immediately, call 911, and provide emergency aid","Rinse with cold water only and reschedule","Ask the client to take an antihistamine and wait 20 minutes"], ans: 1, exp: "Hives and breathing difficulty indicate anaphylaxis, a life-threatening allergic reaction. Immediately remove the product, call 911, and administer emergency first aid while waiting for paramedics." },
    { q: "Material Safety Data Sheets were replaced by Safety Data Sheets (SDS) under which OSHA standard?", opts:["Bloodborne Pathogen Standard","Hazard Communication Standard (HazCom 2012)","General Duty Clause","Chemical Safety Board Standard"], ans: 1, exp: "OSHA's revised Hazard Communication Standard (HazCom 2012) aligned U.S. safety labeling with the Globally Harmonized System, replacing MSDS with the standardized 16-section SDS format." },
    { q: "An example of direct transmission route for infection is:", opts:["A pathogen traveling through the air via droplets","Touching a contaminated door handle then touching your face","Sharing contaminated implements directly with another person","Reading an instruction label on a chemical bottle"], ans: 2, exp: "Direct transmission occurs when pathogens pass directly from one person to another through touch or shared implements. Indirect transmission occurs via contaminated surfaces or objects." },
    { q: "Proper hand hygiene in the salon requires washing hands for at least:", opts:["5 seconds","10 seconds","20 seconds","60 seconds"], ans: 2, exp: "The CDC recommends scrubbing hands for at least 20 seconds with soap and water to effectively remove or kill pathogens before and after every client contact." },
    { q: "An electrocution hazard in the salon is most likely to result from:", opts:["Using a low-wattage blow dryer","Operating electrical appliances near water sources","Storing implements in a dry drawer","Using cord organizers"], ans: 1, exp: "Water is an excellent conductor of electricity. Using electrical tools near sinks or damp areas dramatically increases electrocution risk. All appliances should be kept away from water." },
    { q: "Which of the following is classified as a fungal infection?", opts:["Impetigo","Tinea capitis (ringworm of the scalp)","Herpes simplex","Folliculitis"], ans: 1, exp: "Tinea capitis is a fungal infection of the scalp caused by dermatophyte fungi. It appears as scaly patches and hair loss, is highly contagious, and is a contraindication for salon services." },
  ],
  cc: [
    { q: "During a client consultation, the cosmetologist notices the client has an inflamed possibly infected scalp condition. The best course of action is to:", opts:["Proceed with the chemical service using extra care","Apply a medicated treatment and continue","Decline the service and recommend the client consult a physician","Document the condition and perform a simple trim only"], ans: 2, exp: "Any inflamed, infected, or undiagnosed scalp condition is a contraindication for salon services. Referring the client to a medical professional protects their health and the cosmetologist's license." },
    { q: "An allergy (patch) test for a hair color product must be performed:", opts:["Immediately before the color application","24 to 48 hours before the service","Only on first-time color clients","Every six months regardless of service frequency"], ans: 1, exp: "California BBC regulations and manufacturer guidelines require patch testing 24-48 hours before applying oxidative hair color, allowing time for an allergic reaction to develop and be identified." },
    { q: "The hair analysis step of a client consultation involves assessing all of the following EXCEPT:", opts:["Hair texture","Hair porosity","Hair elasticity","Hair color preference"], ans: 3, exp: "Hair analysis evaluates physical properties including texture, porosity, elasticity, and density to determine appropriate services. Color preference is a design consultation question, not a hair analysis finding." },
    { q: "A client intake form (health history) is used primarily to:", opts:["Determine how much to charge the client","Identify contraindications that may affect service safety","Record the client's style preferences","Track loyalty reward points"], ans: 1, exp: "Client intake forms help identify contraindications such as medical conditions, medications, allergies, or recent treatments that could make a service unsafe or require modification." },
    { q: "Which nail condition would be a contraindication for a standard manicure service?", opts:["Short natural nails","Ridged nails","Onychomycosis (nail fungus)","Soft nails"], ans: 2, exp: "Onychomycosis is a fungal infection of the nail. Performing services on infected nails risks spreading the infection to other clients through contaminated implements." },
    { q: "Low hair elasticity indicates that the hair:", opts:["Has a tight cuticle layer","Is resistant to color","Is overly porous and potentially damaged","Has high protein content"], ans: 2, exp: "Elasticity measures the hair's ability to stretch and return. Low elasticity indicates chemical damage, excessive porosity, or protein depletion, signaling that strong chemical services may cause breakage." },
    { q: "When should a cosmetologist recommend a client seek a medical opinion before continuing services?", opts:["When the client requests a drastic color change","When the client has an undiagnosed skin condition or lesion","When the client requests a new hairstyle","When the client has very fine hair"], ans: 1, exp: "Undiagnosed skin or scalp conditions, unusual lesions, or signs of infection should always be evaluated by a medical professional before salon services are performed." },
    { q: "Hair porosity refers to the hair's ability to:", opts:["Withstand mechanical stress without breaking","Absorb and retain moisture and chemicals","Reflect light evenly","Hold a curl when set"], ans: 1, exp: "Porosity is determined by the cuticle's condition. High-porosity hair absorbs chemicals quickly but may not retain them. Low-porosity hair resists absorption and requires longer processing times." },
    { q: "When performing a hair texture analysis, coarse hair is characterized by:", opts:["A small narrow hair shaft with limited strength","A large wide hair shaft with more structural proteins","Extremely high porosity and fragility","Minimal response to chemical services"], ans: 1, exp: "Coarse hair has a large diameter and a strong cortex. It is generally more resistant to chemical processing and requires stronger solutions or longer processing times than fine hair." },
    { q: "A client who has recently undergone chemotherapy should be assessed for:", opts:["Increased chemical processing times","Fragile hair growth and heightened scalp sensitivity","Permanent color incompatibility","Excessive sebum production"], ans: 1, exp: "Chemotherapy can cause hair loss, and any new growth is often fragile and fine with altered texture. Scalp sensitivity is also heightened, making chemical services or aggressive handling risky." },
    { q: "A scalp condition characterized by excessive flaking and dryness without inflammation is most likely:", opts:["Psoriasis","Seborrheic dermatitis","Pityriasis (simple dandruff)","Tinea capitis"], ans: 2, exp: "Pityriasis capitis simplex (simple dandruff) is characterized by dry white flaky scalp skin without redness or inflammation. Unlike seborrheic dermatitis it is not caused by a fungal organism and is not contagious." },
    { q: "Hair density refers to:", opts:["The diameter of each individual hair strand","The number of hair strands per square inch on the scalp","The rate at which hair grows per month","The ratio of terminal to vellus hairs"], ans: 1, exp: "Density describes how many hairs grow per square inch. High-density hair appears full; low-density hair appears sparse. Density affects product selection, cut techniques, and chemical service results." },
    { q: "A client mentions they are taking blood thinners (anticoagulants). This is relevant in a salon setting because:", opts:["Blood thinners make hair color process faster","The client is at greater risk of prolonged bleeding from minor cuts","Blood thinners contraindicate all chemical services","Anticoagulants cause scalp sensitivity to heat"], ans: 1, exp: "Blood-thinning medications reduce the blood's ability to clot. Any cut or abrasion during a service can bleed more extensively, requiring careful technique and adherence to infection control." },
    { q: "A signed client consent or intake form is used to:", opts:["Verbal agreement only","Document informed consent before the service","A service ticket record only","The stylist's personal notes only"], ans: 1, exp: "Documented written consent protects both client and cosmetologist legally. Signed forms record that the client was informed of procedures, potential risks, and contraindications before the service began." },
    { q: "Hair in the anagen phase of the growth cycle is:", opts:["In the resting phase prior to shedding","Actively growing and attached to the dermal papilla","Detached from the papilla and transitioning out","Shed and no longer present in the follicle"], ans: 1, exp: "The anagen phase is the active growth phase. Hair is actively produced by the follicle and attached to the dermal papilla. This phase lasts 2-7 years for scalp hair." },
    { q: "A positive patch test reaction (redness, itching, swelling at the test site) means:", opts:["Normal processing and safe to proceed","The service must not proceed due to sensitization or allergy","Insufficient product concentration for the test","A need to retest with a stronger formula"], ans: 1, exp: "A positive patch test reaction indicates sensitization or allergy to the product. The service must be cancelled to prevent a potentially severe systemic allergic reaction." },
    { q: "Which of the following describes low-porosity (resistant) hair?", opts:["Hair that absorbs product quickly and unevenly","Hair with a tightly closed cuticle that resists moisture and chemical penetration","Hair that has been chemically processed multiple times","Hair with split ends and breakage"], ans: 1, exp: "Low-porosity hair has a compact, tightly closed cuticle. It repels moisture and chemicals, making it challenging to process. Services may require a pre-softening step or higher pH products." },
    { q: "The most common nail disease encountered by cosmetologists that requires a medical referral is:", opts:["Onychorrhexis (brittle nails)","Onychomycosis (nail fungus)","Leukonychia (white spots)","Onychauxis (thick nails)"], ans: 1, exp: "Onychomycosis is a contagious fungal infection that cannot be treated in a salon. Cosmetologists must identify it and refer clients to a physician. Performing services on infected nails risks spreading infection." },
    { q: "Hair structure analysis before chemical services is important because:", opts:["It determines the final style result","It reveals the hair's ability to withstand and respond to chemical processing","It replaces the need for a strand test","It is required by California BBC for every service"], ans: 1, exp: "Understanding structural integrity helps predict how hair will respond to chemicals. Damaged cuticles and cortexes indicate compromised hair that may break, over-process, or produce unpredictable results." },
  ],
  hs: [
    { q: "When using a thermal curling iron, you should test the temperature by:", opts:["Touching the barrel briefly","Holding a tissue or white paper near the iron","Placing it on the client's neck first","Adjusting to maximum heat and waiting 30 seconds"], ans: 1, exp: "Holding white tissue paper near the iron provides a safe temperature check. If the paper scorches the iron is too hot, preventing burns to the client's hair or scalp." },
    { q: "The primary difference between a full wig and a hairpiece (partial) is that a hairpiece:", opts:["Is always made from synthetic fibers","Covers only a portion of the head","Cannot be styled with heat tools","Is attached with surgical adhesive only"], ans: 1, exp: "A hairpiece covers a specific section of the head, adding length, volume, or coverage in targeted areas. A wig covers the entire head. This distinction affects application, maintenance, and removal." },
    { q: "When blow-drying hair, the nozzle should be directed:", opts:["Against the direction of hair growth at all times","Downward along the cuticle to smooth and seal it","Upward from root to tip for maximum volume","Perpendicular to the hair shaft for even heat distribution"], ans: 1, exp: "Directing airflow downward from root toward ends follows the cuticle's natural direction, smoothing and sealing the scales to produce a shinier frizz-free result with less mechanical damage." },
    { q: "A locking or loc style is achieved by:", opts:["Applying chemical relaxers repeatedly","Allowing hair to mat and intertwine naturally or through palm-rolling","Braiding hair tightly to the scalp","Using thermal tools to permanently straighten sections"], ans: 1, exp: "Locs form when hair coils and mats upon itself, either naturally or through techniques like palm-rolling or interlocking. They are a permanent style that cannot be undone without cutting." },
  ],
  hc: [
    { q: "When cutting over-curly or coily hair, the cosmetologist must account for:", opts:["Increased shrinkage when dry","Faster color absorption","Greater elasticity than straight hair","Reduced need for product"], ans: 0, exp: "Coily hair can shrink 50-75 percent when dry. Always cut understanding that the finished dry length will be significantly shorter than the wet cutting length." },
    { q: "The proper angle for holding shears to create a blunt one-length cut is:", opts:["45 degrees to the head","90 degrees with shears parallel to the section","0 degrees with shears pointing upward","At a 30-degree downward angle"], ans: 1, exp: "A blunt cut requires shears held parallel to the guide section, cutting straight across with no elevation or graduation to create a clean even perimeter." },
    { q: "Clipper-over-comb technique is primarily used to:", opts:["Create sharp geometric angles in long hair","Blend and taper short hair especially at the neckline","Remove bulk from thick long hair","Apply color to the hairline"], ans: 1, exp: "Clipper-over-comb blends and tapers short to medium lengths, particularly in fade styles and men's cuts near the neckline and around the ears." },
    { q: "Safe use of a straight razor for texturizing requires that the blade be:", opts:["Reused across multiple clients if cleaned with alcohol","Disposed of after each client in an approved sharps container","Sterilized in an autoclave and reused","Stored in a dry drawer between clients"], ans: 1, exp: "Straight razor blades are single-use items. After use on one client they must be disposed of in an approved sharps container to prevent bloodborne pathogen transmission." },
    { q: "When using shears, the moving blade should be operated by the:", opts:["Ring finger only","Thumb while the fingers hold the still blade stable","Index finger for precision","Either thumb or index finger depending on technique"], ans: 1, exp: "Correct shear technique has the thumb controlling the moving blade while the ring finger rests in the still blade. This provides precision and reduces fatigue." },
  ],
  hcol: [
    { q: "When applying permanent hair color, the developer (hydrogen peroxide) functions to:", opts:["Add artificial pigment to the cuticle","Lift the cuticle and activate the oxidative color molecules","Deposit color only on the cortex","Neutralize the alkaline color mixture"], ans: 1, exp: "Hydrogen peroxide swells the cuticle to allow color molecules to enter the cortex, then oxidizes the color precursors to form full-sized color molecules inside the hair shaft." },
    { q: "A client with natural level 4 hair wants to achieve level 8. How many levels of lift are required?", opts:["2 levels","4 levels","6 levels","8 levels"], ans: 1, exp: "Levels are numbered 1 (darkest) to 10 (lightest). Moving from level 4 to level 8 requires 4 levels of lift. Higher developer volumes or pre-lightening may be needed." },
    { q: "Metallic or progressive hair dyes are contraindicated for oxidative color services because:", opts:["They fade too quickly with developer","The metals react with peroxide to create heat, breakage, or discoloration","They are not registered with the FDA","They prevent the cuticle from opening"], ans: 1, exp: "Metallic dyes contain metal salts that react violently with hydrogen peroxide, causing excessive heat, hair breakage, and unpredictable color results." },
    { q: "The purpose of a strand test before a color service is to:", opts:["Determine if the client has allergies","Predict the processing time and resulting color","Check hair elasticity only","Satisfy the salon's insurance requirement"], ans: 1, exp: "A strand test allows the cosmetologist to preview the actual color result and verify correct processing time on that client's hair before a full application." },
    { q: "The correct ratio of color to developer is:", opts:["Always 1:1 regardless of product","Determined solely by hair density","Specified by the manufacturer and may vary by product line","Always 1:2 in professional settings"], ans: 2, exp: "Color-to-developer ratios vary by brand and formula. Always follow the manufacturer's instructions for proper consistency and color development." },
    { q: "Toning after lightening is performed primarily to:", opts:["Add moisture to bleached hair","Neutralize unwanted brassy or yellow tones","Increase the level of lift achieved","Prevent damage from future chemical services"], ans: 1, exp: "Pre-lightened hair contains warm undertones. Toners neutralize these tones to achieve the desired cool, neutral, or custom final color." },
    { q: "Hair that has been previously color-treated should be:", opts:["Always stripped before any new color application","Patch tested and strand tested before chemical services","Lightened with a higher volume developer for faster results","Processed at the same timing as virgin hair"], ans: 1, exp: "Previously processed hair is more porous and unpredictable. Both a patch test and strand test are essential before any new color service." },
    { q: "On the color wheel, the complementary color used to neutralize orange tones is:", opts:["Red","Yellow","Blue","Green"], ans: 2, exp: "Blue is the complement of orange. Blue-based toners and colors neutralize brassy orange undertones, especially in dark hair that has been partially lightened." },
    { q: "A 20-volume (6%) developer is most appropriate for:", opts:["Lightening hair 4-5 levels in a single application","Depositing color with no lift","Lifting hair 1-2 levels while depositing permanent color","Maintaining existing color with a toner only"], ans: 2, exp: "20-volume developer provides approximately 1-2 levels of lift while depositing permanent color. It is the most commonly used developer for standard permanent color applications." },
    { q: "The term virgin hair refers to hair that:", opts:["Has never been cut","Has not been previously chemically processed in any way","Has been lightened but not toned","Has been treated with semi-permanent color only"], ans: 1, exp: "Virgin hair has never been chemically processed. It provides the most predictable and consistent color results." },
    { q: "When performing a highlight service using foils, the weaving technique involves:", opts:["Taking a clean straight parting of hair","Picking up alternating strands from a section to create fine uniform highlights","Applying color to the entire section","Painting color freehand onto the hair surface"], ans: 1, exp: "The weaving technique uses a tail comb to pick up alternating strands from a section, creating fine uniform highlights throughout the section." },
    { q: "A client with level 5 natural hair undergoing balayage will show what underlying pigment when lifted?", opts:["Yellow-green","Red-orange","Blue-violet","Pale yellow"], ans: 1, exp: "At level 5 (light brown), the underlying pigment is red-orange. Understanding underlying pigments is critical for predicting the color result and selecting appropriate toners." },
    { q: "Semi-permanent hair color differs from permanent color because it:", opts:["Contains hydrogen peroxide to lift and deposit","Deposits color only and gradually washes out over several shampoos","Permanently alters the hair's natural melanin","Penetrates the cortex as deeply as permanent color"], ans: 1, exp: "Semi-permanent color contains no developer or ammonia. It gradually fades with each shampoo. It does not lighten hair or permanently alter natural pigment." },
    { q: "The color level system ranges from:", opts:["1 to 5 where 1 is lightest","1 to 10 where 1 is darkest and 10 is lightest","1 to 12 where 12 is platinum","A to Z based on manufacturer coding"], ans: 1, exp: "The professional level system uses 1 (black) to 10 (lightest blonde). This standardized system allows colorists to assess natural levels and plan lift requirements accurately." },
    { q: "Over-bleached highly porous hair should be treated before coloring to:", opts:["Speed up color processing time","Temporarily fill gaps in the cuticle and cortex for more even color absorption","Permanently restore disulfide bonds","Prevent the need for toning"], ans: 1, exp: "Fillers and bond-building treatments temporarily reinforce the hair's structure, reducing hyper-porosity so color absorbs more evenly. Without this step color can deposit unevenly and fade rapidly." },
  ],
  ct: [
    { q: "The active ingredient in alkaline (thio) permanent wave solution that breaks disulfide bonds is:", opts:["Hydrogen peroxide","Ammonium thioglycolate","Sodium hydroxide","Ammonium persulfate"], ans: 1, exp: "Ammonium thioglycolate (ATG) is the reducing agent in alkaline waves. It breaks the disulfide bonds in the cortex, allowing hair to conform to the rod shape." },
    { q: "The neutralizing step of a permanent wave service serves to:", opts:["Remove excess waving solution from the hair","Re-form broken disulfide bonds in their new curved position","Open the cuticle for deeper processing","Condition the hair after waving"], ans: 1, exp: "The neutralizer (hydrogen peroxide) re-oxidizes the reduced disulfide bonds in their new rod-shaped configuration, permanently setting the wave pattern." },
    { q: "A true acid wave has a pH range of approximately:", opts:["3.0 to 4.5","6.0 to 6.5","7.5 to 8.5","9.0 to 9.5"], ans: 1, exp: "True acid waves (pH 6.0-6.5) require heat activation and produce softer shinier waves. Their lower pH is gentler than alkaline waves (pH 8.0-9.5)." },
    { q: "Chemical hair relaxers that use sodium hydroxide (NaOH) are known as:", opts:["Thio relaxers","No-lye relaxers","Lye relaxers","Bisulfite relaxers"], ans: 2, exp: "Lye relaxers contain sodium hydroxide. They are fast-acting and effective but require careful scalp protection. No-lye relaxers use alternative hydroxide bases such as guanidine." },
    { q: "Before applying a chemical relaxer, the cosmetologist should NEVER:", opts:["Analyze the hair texture and condition","Apply a protective base to the scalp","Shampoo the hair immediately before the service","Strand test for processing time"], ans: 2, exp: "Shampooing before a relaxer removes the scalp's natural oil protection, increasing burn risk. A base cream protects the scalp, but shampooing immediately beforehand is contraindicated." },
    { q: "When performing a soft-curl permanent on relaxed hair, the cosmetologist must:", opts:["Use an alkaline wave and standard neutralizer","Use a thio-based curl booster and rearranging lotion only","First apply the curl booster (thio), then the rearranging lotion in sequence","Apply a sodium hydroxide relaxer followed by neutralizer"], ans: 2, exp: "Curl reformation on relaxed hair requires a specific sequence: curl booster (thio) breaks bonds, rearranging lotion configures the curl, then neutralizer re-sets bonds." },
    { q: "Overprocessing during a permanent wave service most commonly results in:", opts:["Insufficient curl","Hair breakage and damaged bonds","Excessive curl tightness","Scalp irritation only"], ans: 1, exp: "Overprocessing breaks too many disulfide bonds, producing mushy inelastic hair prone to breakage. It is caused by leaving solution on too long or using too strong a formula." },
    { q: "The best candidate for a chemical texture service is:", opts:["Client with scalp abrasions from scratching","Client who colored their hair with metallic dye","Client with previously relaxed healthy unstretched hair","Client with signs of active dermatitis on the scalp"], ans: 2, exp: "Healthy relaxed hair without scalp irritation or metallic dye history is the best candidate. The other options are all contraindications for chemical texture services." },
    { q: "After a chemical relaxer service, the neutralizing shampoo is used to:", opts:["Restore shine to processed hair","Stop the chemical action and normalize the hair's pH","Remove product buildup","Pre-condition the hair for styling"], ans: 1, exp: "The neutralizing shampoo stops hydroxide relaxer action by restoring hair pH to approximately 4.5-5.5. Improper neutralization can result in continued structural damage." },
    { q: "The primary difference between a lye and no-lye relaxer is:", opts:["Lye relaxers require neutralizing; no-lye relaxers do not","No-lye relaxers use a different hydroxide base and may require conditioning afterward","Lye relaxers are gentler on the scalp","No-lye relaxers process faster than lye relaxers"], ans: 1, exp: "No-lye relaxers use guanidine, lithium, or potassium hydroxide instead of sodium hydroxide. They are less irritating but may leave calcium deposits, often requiring chelating or conditioning treatment afterward." },
    { q: "The size of the perm rod affects the resulting curl in that:", opts:["Larger rods create tighter curls; smaller rods produce looser waves","Smaller rods create tighter curls; larger rods produce looser waves","Rod size only affects depth of wave not tightness","All rods produce the same curl size with sufficient processing time"], ans: 1, exp: "The smaller the rod, the tighter the resulting curl. Larger rods produce loose waves or body waves. Rod selection must consider the client's natural texture and desired result." },
    { q: "An endothermic (heat-activated) perm wave requires:", opts:["A higher pH formula than alkaline waves","An external heat source such as a dryer to activate the processing","No rinsing before neutralizing","A lower concentration of ammonium thioglycolate than alkaline waves"], ans: 1, exp: "Endothermic waves (acid waves) require an external heat source, typically a preheated hood dryer, to activate and accelerate chemical processing." },
    { q: "A keratin smoothing treatment differs from a chemical relaxer because:", opts:["It permanently breaks disulfide bonds like a relaxer","It temporarily smooths and straightens the hair's surface without permanently altering the bond structure","It uses sodium hydroxide as its active ingredient","It can only be performed on virgin unprocessed hair"], ans: 1, exp: "Keratin treatments coat the hair with a keratin-based formula heat-sealed into the cuticle. They reduce frizz temporarily but do not permanently break disulfide bonds as a relaxer does." },
    { q: "After wrapping hair on perm rods, the waving solution is applied:", opts:["Before wrapping to pre-soften the hair","Starting at the nape and working toward the top","Starting at the top and working toward the nape","After 5 minutes of heat application"], ans: 1, exp: "Waving solution is applied to already-wrapped rods beginning at the nape and working toward the top, ensuring even processing since nape rods are wrapped and processed first." },
    { q: "The processing time for a permanent wave is complete when:", opts:["Exactly 20 minutes have elapsed regardless of hair type","A test curl shows the desired S-pattern when unrolled approximately halfway from the rod","The hair has shrunk tightly against the rod","The hair feels dry to the touch through the rod"], ans: 1, exp: "The test curl check is performed by gently unrolling a rod about halfway and checking for the desired S-pattern. This confirms adequate processing without over-processing." },
    { q: "Which of the following is NOT a contraindication for a permanent wave service?", opts:["Hair with active breakage or splits","Previously chemically straightened hair that has not grown out","Fine healthy natural hair with normal elasticity","Hair treated with a metallic or compound dye"], ans: 2, exp: "Fine healthy natural hair with normal elasticity is a good candidate for a permanent wave. All other options present contraindications that increase the risk of damage or unpredictable results." },
  ],
  sc: [
    { q: "During a facial massage, effleurage movements are used primarily to:", opts:["Stimulate deeper muscle tissue","Begin and end the massage sequence with light gliding strokes","Break up scar tissue","Increase blood circulation to the dermis"], ans: 1, exp: "Effleurage (light gliding strokes) opens and closes massage sequences, relaxes the client, and distributes product. It is the most commonly used movement in cosmetology facials." },
    { q: "Mechanical exfoliation removes dead skin cells using:", opts:["Chemical acids such as AHA or BHA","Physical abrasion through tools, scrubs, or dermaplaning","Heat application","High-frequency electrical current"], ans: 1, exp: "Mechanical exfoliation uses friction from microdermabrasion, exfoliating scrubs, brushes, or dermaplaning to physically remove dead cells. Chemical exfoliation uses acids to dissolve bonds holding dead cells." },
    { q: "When performing a scalp treatment, which condition would contraindicate the service?", opts:["Dry flaky scalp","Open wounds or abrasions on the scalp","Fine hair","Normal scalp with occasional dryness"], ans: 1, exp: "Open wounds, abrasions, or sores on the scalp are contraindications for scalp treatments. Performing services on broken skin risks infection, chemical irritation, and cross-contamination." },
    { q: "Petrissage massage movements involve:", opts:["Long gliding strokes in one direction","Kneading and lifting of the skin and muscle tissue","Rapid tapping or slapping movements","Gentle vibration applied with fingertips"], ans: 1, exp: "Petrissage uses kneading, lifting, squeezing, and rolling movements to stimulate deeper tissues, improve circulation, and work on muscle tension. It is more stimulating than effleurage." },
    { q: "A hot towel applied during a facial service is used to:", opts:["Permanently open pores","Soften the skin and prepare it for cleansing or extraction","Apply chemical peeling agents safely","Cool the skin after exfoliation"], ans: 1, exp: "Hot towels soften the skin and temporarily dilate pores, making cleansing, extractions, and product penetration more effective. They should be applied at a safe comfortable temperature." },
    { q: "Alpha hydroxy acids (AHAs) used in cosmetology-level skin care work by:", opts:["Physically scrubbing away dead skin cells","Dissolving the bonds between dead skin cells to promote exfoliation","Permanently removing the top layer of the dermis","Sterilizing the skin surface before treatment"], ans: 1, exp: "AHAs (glycolic, lactic, mandelic acid) dissolve the intercellular bonds holding dead corneocytes to the skin surface, revealing fresher skin beneath without physical scrubbing." },
    { q: "Safe removal of calluses during a pedicure service requires:", opts:["A razor blade or callus cutter for hard calluses","A pumice stone or foot file used on softened skin","Chemical acid peels penetrating to the dermis","Electrical grinders at maximum speed"], ans: 1, exp: "California BBC regulations permit only pumice stones and foot files (not razor blades) for callus removal. The skin should be softened first and removal should be conservative." },
  ],
  ee: [
    { q: "Before applying an eyelash adhesive, the cosmetologist should always:", opts:["Conduct a patch test at least 24 hours in advance","Apply directly to assess sensitivity","Heat the adhesive for better bonding","Use the same adhesive for all clients regardless of sensitivity history"], ans: 0, exp: "Eyelash adhesive (cyanoacrylate-based) can cause allergic reactions. A patch test 24 hours prior screens for sensitivity, especially critical near the delicate eye area." },
    { q: "Safe removal of strip eyelash enhancements requires:", opts:["Peeling from the outer corner with dry hands","Using an oil-based remover or adhesive solvent and gently releasing the bond","Soaking in hot water for 10 minutes","Trimming the lashes off at the base"], ans: 1, exp: "An oil-based or purpose-designed adhesive remover dissolves the bond without pulling on natural lashes or damaging the eyelid. Forceful removal causes lash loss and irritation." },
    { q: "Eyebrow or eyelash tinting is a service that requires special caution because:", opts:["The products are regulated by the FDA as cosmetics only","Tinting products near the eyes can cause serious reactions if they enter the eye","The color result is always permanent","Products must be mixed with hydrogen peroxide at a 1:3 ratio"], ans: 1, exp: "Tinting dyes near the eyes can cause severe reactions on contact with mucous membranes. Careful application, protective eye pads, and monitoring for reactions are essential." },
    { q: "Chemical eyelash services such as lash lifts use which chemical to reshape the lashes?", opts:["Hydrogen peroxide","Sodium hydroxide","A thioglycolate-based solution similar to permanent wave chemistry","A depilatory cream"], ans: 2, exp: "Lash lifts use a thioglycolate-based solution to break and reform the disulfide bonds in the lash structure, curling lashes against a silicone shield using the same chemistry as a permanent wave." },
    { q: "When tinting eyebrows, the product should be kept away from:", opts:["The arch of the brow","Any skin beyond the brow border only","The eye itself and surrounding mucous membranes","The client's hairline"], ans: 2, exp: "Tinting products must never contact the eye, surrounding mucous membranes, or inner corners. Eye pads or petroleum jelly are used to protect the eyes during brow or lash tinting." },
    { q: "Individual lash extensions are applied:", opts:["Directly onto the eyelid skin","One extension attached to one natural lash using lash adhesive","In clusters glued to the lash line at once","Using a heated bonding tool"], ans: 1, exp: "Individual lash extensions are attached one-to-one: each extension is bonded to a single natural lash using professional adhesive, never to the eyelid skin. This prevents follicle damage and allows for natural growth cycles." },
  ],
  hr: [
    { q: "The main reason for wearing gloves during a waxing service is:", opts:["To improve grip on wax applicators","To prevent cross-contamination with blood or body fluids","To protect the cosmetologist's hands from wax burns","To meet salon insurance requirements"], ans: 1, exp: "Infection control is the primary reason for gloves during waxing. Waxing causes micro-abrasions exposing skin to blood or body fluids, requiring standard precautions to prevent pathogen transmission." },
    { q: "Double-dipping a waxing spatula into a communal wax pot is prohibited because:", opts:["It wastes product","It cools the wax to an ineffective temperature","It introduces bacteria from the client's skin into the wax pot","It thickens the wax too quickly"], ans: 2, exp: "Double-dipping introduces bacteria and potentially bloodborne pathogens from the client's skin into the shared wax pot. A fresh spatula must be used for each application." },
    { q: "Threading as a hair removal technique removes hair by:", opts:["Applying a chemical depilatory to the root","Using a twisted thread to trap and pull hair from the follicle","Waxing with natural beeswax only","Cutting hair at the surface with a razor"], ans: 1, exp: "Threading uses a twisted thread to trap and epilate individual hairs at the follicle level. It is a precise technique commonly used for eyebrow shaping and facial hair removal." },
    { q: "A contraindication for waxing services includes a client who is currently using:", opts:["Vitamin C serums","Retinoids or isotretinoin (Accutane)","SPF moisturizers","Caffeine-based eye creams"], ans: 1, exp: "Retinoids and isotretinoin thin the skin significantly. Waxing on thinned skin can tear it, causing severe burns and scarring. This is a well-documented contraindication." },
    { q: "Sugaring as a hair removal method differs from traditional waxing because:", opts:["Sugaring removes hair against the direction of growth while wax goes with growth","Sugaring is applied against hair growth and removed in the direction of hair growth","Sugaring uses a chemical depilatory base","Sugaring can only be used on the legs"], ans: 1, exp: "Traditional wax is applied with hair growth and removed against it. Sugaring paste is typically applied against the direction of growth and removed in the direction of growth." },
    { q: "After a waxing service, the skin may appear red or slightly inflamed. The cosmetologist should:", opts:["Apply more wax to soothe the area","Recommend the client apply soothing products and avoid sun exposure","Send the client home with a prescription anti-inflammatory","Apply hydrogen peroxide to the area"], ans: 1, exp: "Post-waxing redness is a normal reaction. Advise soothing products such as aloe, avoid sun, and no tight clothing or heat for 24 hours." },
    { q: "Depilatories work by:", opts:["Pulling hair from the root","Temporarily bleaching the hair","Chemically dissolving the protein structure of the hair shaft","Cutting the hair at the skin surface"], ans: 2, exp: "Chemical depilatories use thioglycolate compounds to break down hair's keratin protein structure at or below the skin surface. Results last longer than shaving but shorter than waxing." },
    { q: "Before applying wax, the cosmetologist should check the wax temperature by:", opts:["Applying a small amount to the client's inner wrist","Testing on their own inner wrist first","Visually checking the wax consistency alone","Testing on the client's desired treatment area without warning"], ans: 0, exp: "Wax temperature should be tested on a small area of the client's inner wrist before applying to the treatment area. This prevents burns from overheated wax and lets the client confirm comfort." },
    { q: "Hard wax (stripless wax) is removed in which direction?", opts:["With the direction of hair growth","Against the direction of hair growth","Sideways across the skin","Slowly peeling upward"], ans: 1, exp: "Hard wax is removed against the direction of hair growth while keeping the skin taut. The wax hardens around the hair, allowing it to be lifted without a strip, making it suitable for sensitive areas." },
    { q: "Which of the following is an appropriate area for soft wax application followed by strip removal?", opts:["Inside the nose","The inner ear canal","The lower leg","The eyeball area"], ans: 2, exp: "Soft (strip) wax is appropriate for larger areas such as legs, arms, and back. It should never be applied to mucous membranes, the inner ear, or near the eyes." },
  ],
  nc: [
    { q: "The proper ventilation requirement for a nail service area is intended to protect against:", opts:["Humidity that causes polish to lift","Dust from filing only","Vapors and particulate matter from nail products","Noise from electric files"], ans: 2, exp: "Nail products release potentially harmful vapors and particulate matter. Adequate local exhaust ventilation or HEPA filtration protects both technicians and clients from respiratory harm." },
    { q: "Safe cuticle removal during a manicure requires:", opts:["Using a metal pusher to aggressively remove all cuticle tissue","Softening the cuticle first then gently pushing back live tissue only","Cutting the cuticle completely for a clean finish","Applying acetone directly to dissolve the cuticle"], ans: 1, exp: "Only dead cuticle (pterygium) should be removed or pushed back. Living cuticle protects the nail matrix. Aggressive cutting risks pain, bleeding, and infection." },
    { q: "Onycholysis is a nail condition characterized by:", opts:["Thickening and yellowing of the nail plate","Separation of the nail plate from the nail bed","White spots beneath the nail plate","Deep vertical ridges in the nail surface"], ans: 1, exp: "Onycholysis is the painless separation of the nail plate from the nail bed, caused by trauma, psoriasis, fungal infection, or chemical exposure. It contraindicates nail enhancement services." },
    { q: "When performing a pedicure, callus removal should be done using:", opts:["A metal callus grater applied firmly to all areas","A pumice stone or foot file on softened skin only","A razor blade for thick calluses","Chemical peel agents that penetrate to the dermis"], ans: 1, exp: "California BBC regulations allow only pumice stones and foot files for callus removal. Skin should be softened first and removal should be conservative to avoid injury." },
    { q: "Nail infection control procedures require that files and buffers used on a client:", opts:["Be sanitized with alcohol spray between clients","Be discarded after single use or thoroughly disinfected if non-porous","Be stored in the nail technician's kit between uses","Be replaced only when visibly damaged"], ans: 1, exp: "Most nail files are porous and must be single-use per client. Non-porous implements can be disinfected; porous ones should be discarded to prevent cross-contamination." },
    { q: "The chemical in nail products known as the Toxic Trio that is associated with reproductive harm is:", opts:["Acetone","Ethyl methacrylate","Toluene","Isopropyl alcohol"], ans: 2, exp: "The Toxic Trio (formaldehyde, toluene, and dibutyl phthalate) are chemicals of concern in nail products. Toluene is a solvent linked to reproductive toxicity and neurological effects with chronic exposure." },
    { q: "Artificial nail enhancements should NOT be applied when the client presents with:", opts:["Short natural nails","Nails with horizontal ridges (Beau's lines)","Active nail fungus (onychomycosis)","Mild nail brittleness"], ans: 2, exp: "Active onychomycosis contraindicates enhancements. Applying acrylics or gel over infected nails traps moisture, worsens infection, and risks spreading pathogens to implements and other clients." },
    { q: "During artificial nail removal, the safest method involves:", opts:["Prying the enhancement off with a metal implement","Soaking in the appropriate solvent until the product softens","Filing the nail down to the natural plate aggressively","Clipping the enhancement off with nail cutters"], ans: 1, exp: "Soaking in appropriate solvent is the safest removal method. Prying, forcing, or aggressive filing damages the natural nail plate and surrounding tissue." },
    { q: "The nail matrix is located:", opts:["At the free edge of the nail","Under the visible nail plate","In the skin surrounding the nail","At the base of the nail under the lunula and proximal nail fold"], ans: 3, exp: "The nail matrix is the growth center of the nail, located at the base beneath the proximal nail fold and lunula. Damage to the matrix can permanently alter nail growth, shape, and thickness." },
    { q: "Beau's lines are nail conditions characterized by:", opts:["Yellow thickened nail plates","Transverse (horizontal) grooves across the nail plate","White patches on the nail surface","Spoon-shaped nails that curve upward"], ans: 1, exp: "Beau's lines are horizontal grooves caused by a temporary interruption in nail growth from illness, high fever, malnutrition, or trauma. They grow out over time and are not contagious." },
    { q: "Which nail enhancement system uses a liquid monomer and powder polymer?", opts:["Gel nails (UV/LED)","Acrylic nail system","Nail wraps (silk/fiberglass)","Dip powder system (SNS)"], ans: 1, exp: "The acrylic system combines a liquid monomer (ethyl methacrylate) with a powder polymer. When mixed they form a pliable bead that hardens as it polymerizes, distinct from gel systems and dip powder." },
    { q: "Nail station ventilation requires managing particulate matter specifically because:", opts:["Particulate dust from filing can irritate eyes, nose, throat, and lungs","Dust particles cause gel nails to cure more slowly","Filing dust is flammable under salon lighting","Particulate matter discolors the nail station surface"], ans: 0, exp: "Fine dust particles generated during nail filing (especially acrylics and gels) can be inhaled deep into the lungs, potentially causing respiratory irritation or sensitization over time. Local exhaust ventilation captures this dust at the source." },
  ],
};
